{
  "answer": "In the opening couplet of this ghazal, Ghalib states that every gesture (*ishāre*) of the beloved contains a hidden sign or mark (*nishaan*), implying layers of unspoken meaning or coquetry beneath the surface. Their displays of love (*mohabbat*) only arouse further suspicion (*gumaān*) of something else entirely—perhaps insincerity, artifice, or deeper intent.[^1]\n\nThe full translation of the couplet reads:  \n\"In every gesture lies a hidden strain;  \nTheir love itself is something else again.\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/60-hai-baske-har-ek-unke-ishaare-mein-nishaan-aur/translation/#p-f941cf).",
